        Returns:

      • containsAny

        public static boolean containsAny(CharSequence target,
                                  CharSequence source)
        Returns true if any of the characters in the source CharSequence are also contained within the target CharSequence.

        Returns false if either the source or the target CharSequence is null or empty.

        (Note that both String and StringBuilder implement the CharSequence interface.)

        Parameters:
        target - CharSequence in which to search for the characters which comprise the source CharSequence
        source - CharSequence whose characters should be searched for within the target CharSequence
        Returns:
        true if neither the target nor the source is null nor empty and if the characters contained within target are a superset of those contained within source

      • narrowestCommonType

        public static Class<?> narrowestCommonType(Collection<Class<?>> types)
                                    throws IllegalStateException
        Returns the narrowest common type (NCT) from a Collection of types.

        Attempts to infer the narrowest common type (NCT) which can be used to describe the collection of types passed as the argument. For example, if a Float and a Double are passed, the narrowest type which can be used to describe both of those pieces of data without any loss of precision is the Double type. But if a Float and a Byte are passed, these both can be fully described by a Float. If an Integer and a Long are passed, Long is the NCT.

        If any numeric and non-numeric types are both contained within types, then the NCT is necessarily String. The same goes for mixed non-numeric types like Character and LocalDateTime.

        Parameters:
        types - a Collection of types for which the NCT should be found
        Returns:
        the NCT from the given Collection of types
        Throws:
        IllegalStateException - when the NCT cannot be determined or if types is null or empty

      • transpose

        public static <T> List<List<T>> transpose(List<List<T>> listOfLists)
        Transposes a List<List<T>> (List of Lists) and returns the result.

        If the given listOfLists contains any null Lists (as rows), then the returned transposed List<List<T>> will containnull values down that row's corresponding column.

        Type Parameters:
        T - type of objects contained within the inner Lists
        Parameters:
        listOfLists - List of Lists to transpose
        Returns:
        listOfLists, transposed, with null values representing empty or missing "cells"

      • similarity

        public static <U,T extends Iterable<U>> double similarity(T A,
                                                          T B)
        Returns the "similarity" of two Iterables on a scale of [0.0, 1.0].

        If the two Iterables are of different lengths, or either or both of the Iterables are null, they are not comparable and this method returns a similarity of 0.0.

        Otherwise, the Iterables are compared element-by-element with the equals() method of the element from A. For each pair of elements for which equals() returns true, a "similarity" counter is incremented. Once all pairs of elements have been compared, similarity is divided by the number of elements in the Iterables and the result is returned as a double.

        The two Iterables must contain the same class of data (U), for instance, two List<String>s can be compared, or a List<String> and a Set<String>, but not a List<String> and a List<Boolean>. If a generic Iterable is used (ie. List, with no type specified), the type is asumed to be Object. So if two generic Iterables are compared, they will both be assumed to contain Objects, which -- though it will not throw any errors -- is usually not what you want.

        See Iterable for all classes and subinterfaces which implement the Iterable interface. Ones of note are Collection, List, and Set.

        Type Parameters:
        U - type of objects contained within the Iterables
        T - Iterable<U> or a subclass
        Parameters:
        A - first Iterable to compare
        B - second Iterable to compare
        Returns:
        the "similarity" of two Iterables on a scale of [0.0, 1.0]
